Review

Database generally divided into two:
Relational Database
Non-Relational Database

Review: Relational Database

Multiple tables
Can be joined
Most common. Widely used
Example: MySQL, PostgreSQL, SQLServer, Oracle

Review: Non-Relational Database (NoSQL)

No Table, No Structure --> Collections
Not support join
Alternative. Depend on use case
Example: MongoDB, Redis

Our Focus: Relational Database

Data Modeling

A way to visualize a data storage system
Easier to discuss and consult with stakeholders
Blueprint of actual implementation
To avoid risk in implementation

Type of Model

Conceptual
Logical
Physical

Conceptual

Focused on the overall structure
Contain entities
Contain relationship between entities

Logical

Detail of conceptual model
Contain attributes
May contain data types in high-level name
Contain detail relationship between entities

Phisical

Vendor-specific of logical model
Contain data types with specific vendor
Contain primary keys, foreign keys, and indexes

Entity Relational Diagram

ERD visually represents the relationships between multiple entities
ERD is bidirectional diagram, so that the relationship between two entities can be read clearly
The way to interpret ERDs called ERDish by Oracle Academy

Terminology

Entity --> Class/Object
Attribute --> Attribute/Property
Relationship

Cardinality Modality

Cardinality: maximum instance involved in relationship
Modality: minimum instance involved in relationship
In general: One and Many, and Optional
Visualized using Chen or Crow Foot Notation

Cardinality: Chen's Notation

Cardinality: Crow's Foot Notation
